<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Please! This guy's credibility is negative and heading down fast. It's no longer fun arguing with quacks like this.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So far your argument has been less than weak – no doubt as to why you now attack the person.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Until you've proven that you've done real work on plasma interactions with a pusher plate as in aplication on Orion (not A-bomb tests which have many differences from nuclear pulse rocketry), and you've proven thatyou're notjust arguing from ignorance and pre-conceived notions, then you've go no credibility.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
And you have? No? What does that say about your credibility?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> I haven't boasted that I'm a genius expert mathematician and theoretical physicist as you have.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
And of course, you can point out exactly where I made that claim. No?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> The best you have, as somebody pointed out, is conspiracy theories about the Orion workers hoaxing it, and NASA discovering the hoax and disregarding it</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
You’ve not shown me NASA’s official position on Orion as you’ve presented it; therefore it is easy to come to the conclusion they knew it wouldn’t work. That possibility would never enter your limited event horizon.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Why did they waste money on these when they &quot;know Orion is psuedo science and completely impossible&quot;?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The commissioning of studies costs money, or didn’t you know that? Can you argue that NASA never once spent money on something that didn’t work?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> andas I quoted from Dyson's book</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I’m getting a little tired of hearing quotes from Dyson’s book. You seem to hold it aloft like some sort of ancient scroll or bible. Let’s get it straight – Dyson has a biased opinion and an agenda to sell his book. You could say the same thing about Stephen Hawking – one might read his books but never learn a thing about physics.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> You're consistently assuming that the only ones who believe that Orion was a realistic proposal, and would in fact work are we here, and G. and F. Dyson.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That is correct.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Numerous hard scientist/engineer authors have written about it for the layman</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
