<br>
It’s nice to see a discussion on Orion’s feasibility, but this discussion has more flame than fact. Everyone stop blaming each other for being biased, one sided, lemming brained <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  and other stuff. This will bring us nowhere and probably result in an even greater flame war than is needed.<br>
<br>
About the Orion, I seriously doubt that the team behind Orion would somehow forget to see if the pusher-plates would survive the torture from the nuclear pulse units. It was expressed by Dyson (don’t nail me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/nerd.gif ALT="8o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) that they where very concerned about this. I don’t have access to a nuke so that I could test it, but I think it would be possible for me, to get hold of some software that would simulate it.<br>
<br>
A steel pusher-plate should survive a blast of plasma several hundreds of degrees Celsius, if the blast last for a short while. 200 blasts would erode a big great chunk of the plate, unless you could get it to eat something else instead. The pusher-plate would not destabilise due to gamma radiation, but I would build up a great deal of heat from excess x-rays and blackbody radiation. It would become hotter and hotter so there would have to be considerable break between the series of explosions, since a hotter plate is more brittle.<br>
<br>
I think the Orion is possible, but I don’t think it’s practical. Oh sure it’s better than chemical rockets, but they are not practical, they are a sick sad joke. There are other ways into space, all of whom requires nuclear power in some form to be practical, like the space elevator and ion-drives.<br>
<br>
Let's just keep the Orion where it is and let it die along with all of the 50's imageneering. It's a nice dream, but there are better dreams. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/14/03 3:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=141>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Am I the only one who finds this humerous. </span><hr size=1> Orion is workable, practical,and fesaible,, and able to carry payloads of millions of tons quickly to the planets wth a flight time of weeks , or to travel slowly to the nearest stars with 40 to 50  years  of flight time..<br>
