<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; It’s nice to see a discussion on Orion’s feasibility, but this discussion has more flame than fact. Everyone stop blaming each other for being biased, one sided, lemming brained and other stuff.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I like to think I've not flamed anybody. I've attacked the idea that butchering the scientific method to suit your own views is antithetical to logical study of a subject.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I seriously doubt that the team behind Orion would somehow forget to see if the pusher-plates would survive the torture from the nuclear pulse units.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I doubt that it's a vast conspiracy which says that they didn't consider this issue very carefully and then supposedly hid the unfavorable results of their studies.<br>
The issue here in this thread boils down to a question of whether the favorable reporting of Orion we relate to readers is fraudulent, and NASA actually pounded the nails into the coffin of Orion's feasibility in the '60s.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I don’t have access to a nuke so that I could test it, but I think it would be possible for me, to get hold of some software that would simulate it.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
G.Dyson reported in the &quot;Orion lemming's Bible&quot; that later generations of the same software they used in the '60s is in use today in industrial applications. I don't urge people to read the book to give money to G.Dyson (I've read most of it standing up in bookstores). He includes extensive bibliography notes and other things which could be used to follow up on stuff reported in the book. Not fiction or cartoons but real govpubs and technical articles.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I think the Orion is possible, but I don’t think it’s practical... There are other ways into space, all of whom requires nuclear power in some form to be practical, like the space elevator and ion-drives.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Several points:<br>
If beanstalks or tethers or hypersonic skyhooks come along, fine. They don't help us get big payloads to the planets quickly.<br>
Ion won't get you into space. It will get you around space, but Orion does it before your crew dies of old age... Chemicals also are of some limited use in the inner solar system, but long-duration exposure does harm, somewhat less than ion drive.<br>
 You won't use ion drive for crewed missions. NPR gets them there (with vast amounts of the starting mass being cargo &amp; safeties) while the ion driven ship is slowly speeding up to gradually get into its trans-Mars interplanetary trajectory.<br>
<br>
If you've got the political will to use NTR or even nuclear-powered VASIMR, then you can use NPR with a bit of international cooperation. VASIMR, ICAN and Daedalus require new breakthroughs, and smaller innovation gets Orion type NPR flying sooner.<br>
<br>
I don't necessarily urge using Orion for launch from the ground, unless it's proven that a later generation version is clean &amp; safe.<br>
 Many points against it here: political palatability -even if clean- safety &amp; reliability of the firing mechanisms &amp; bombs in the hectic &amp; hazardous launch environment, etc.<br>
There are big differences between launch and interplanetary space travel requirements. Many things work for launch, including perfectly clean &amp; well known H/O rockets.<br>
Few things as well known work well in space; It takes ~8km/sec to get to orbit, and <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">50</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->km/sec to get to Mars in 6 weeks, and only NPR does this, and only Orion is workable now, with readily understood technology. No containment or channeling of fusing plasma, no containment of antiprotons, no new inventions.<br>
Read the NASA MSFC paper on EPPP, and pay particular attention to their comments on the &quot;mark-1&quot; 10 meter ship. Lift its parts to HEO with STS or Energia HLVs, and we've got a great interplanetary ship -<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>now</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Probably cost less to start this program than they're spending now keeping the Shuttle orbiter Death-Traps flying.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Let's just keep the Orion where it is and let it die along with all of the 50's imageneering. It's a nice dream, but there are better dreams.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Better dreams for interplanetary travel which allow rapid robust routine &amp; safe travel among the Solar system, using technology readily understood in the '50s and '60s, and even more useful &amp; cost effective today?<br>
<br>
Tim1965<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; There are better methods of nuclear propulsion that can be used other then orion: such ion drives, plasma drives, Deadalas class fusion microexplosion drives, and antimatter- matter annhilation powered drives et el.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Like I've said before, There are a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>few</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> other proposals which might equal Orion's preformance (only a very few), but with Orion, the greatest technical hurdles are akin to innovating a grease-mist-sprayer to cover a 10 or 40 meter plate in between 1 per 20 second &gt;=20KT pulses. They planned to use the compression of the shocks to generate steam to run generator turbines, cycle the loading mechanism, eject the bombs, and pump the sprayer.<br>
Propellant for the bombs for the return trip (~60% of the return trip bombs mass) is made either from in-situ materials (ices), or even the crew's own biological wastes...<br>
 Tell me there are better options than this one, which uses up tons of weapons-grade fissionables, and even more tons of sh!t<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 4/15/03 3:43:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theredcomin>theredcomin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/18/03 9:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=143>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Am I the only one who finds this humerous. </span><hr size=1> I've read this thread from the beginning, hoping it might have something interesting to add to a fundamentally interesting topic.<br>
<br>
Instead we have been treated to the inannities of Q66stang or whatever he calls him/her self. It's clear his/her motto is &quot;I've made up my tiny mind. Don't confuse me with the facts.&quot;<br>
<br>
I've got a suggestion for how to get us back onto an interesting discussion again: just ignore Q66stang's posts. It's obvious nothing will persuade him/her to moderate his/her purile views, and we should not encourage him/her by rising to the bait.<br>
<br>
=======<br>
<br>
So, moving right along:<br>
<br>
I've got a copy of the BIS Project Daedelus Report (or, to be strictly accurate, I've loaned it to someone and would like it back) but from what I can recall of it, it would seem to me that the future of manned spaceflight within the Solar System probably lies with a Orion/Daedelus craft, using pulsed fusion rather than fission. This is partly because we can see our way ahead to having the technology to create fusion reactions in tiny pellets by use of lasers, and these explosions can be both much smaller and much more frequent than Orion proposed. Also, the radiation danger will be greatly reduced, and at the same time the delta-V (or mass ratio) possible will be much higher.<br>
<br>
However, I don't see this ever being used as an Earth-to-LEO lifting system. For a start, it'll never get past Greenpeace, etc., and the governments than run scared of them. But it's a helluva way to get round the Solar System!<br>
<br>
But this still leaves us looking for a cheap way to deliver masses of stuff and peole into LEO. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 412<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/18/03 2:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=144>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Again, I'm drawn back to Orion as simple</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; the future of manned spaceflight within the Solar System probably lies with a Orion/Daedelus craft, using pulsed fusion rather than fission.<br>
&gt;This is partly because we can see our way ahead to having the technology to create fusion reactions in tiny pellets by use of lasers...<br>
&gt;Also, the radiation danger will be greatly reduced, and at the same time the delta-V (or mass ratio) possible will be much higher.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Hadn't seen anything saying that mass ratios or delta-V is higher than an old fission Orion. Given the technology to make these, fission bomb Orion is also improved, so it's a toss-up.<br>
 The question is fuel. With large scale activity in space, fission power plants might be as useful as a wind-driven generator on an airplane -sure it works, but why? Solar is everywhere and the main feedstock is metal-film mirror instead of highly refined U ores.<br>
OTOH, it is simple and useful as a power source, and even ground-based power plants could provide a cheap fuel source for Orion (Breeder cycle).<br>
<br>
For micro-fusion, it's a technical challenge to ignite the pellets and again, improvements here only help Orion, too. With easy solutions to the problems with ICAN/ACMF, Daedalus, or mini-orion, old fashioned fission bombs are also cheaper &amp; simpler.<br>
<br>
If we get out to a source of He3 (better than the Moon), then it's a lot better. Maybe even clean enough for a fusion-pulse powered atmospheric booster...<br>
I'd also like to learn more about the 11Boron7 + proton reaction. A certain amount of protons being bombarded onto a certain molecule of an isotope of Boron and the reaction gives off extremely energetic He atoms minus the electrons, easily directed by fields -and no ionizing radiation whatsoever.<br>
<br>
However, I don't see this ever being used as an Earth-to-LEO lifting system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/18/03 10:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=145>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion</span><hr size=1> While I think ongoing discussion of Orion is probably a good thing, if only as a baseline against which to judge alternatives. More research on my part has not reversed my previous opinion that there are numerous propulsion solution that simply make more sense than NPR.<br>
<br>
Orion has some serious problems.  For example, the Orion pusher plate was designed so that its thickness at any given point matched the momentum of the plasma stream that would impact it.  This was done so that the entire plate would experience uniform acceleration and not be ripped apart by the difference in exerted force from the center to the perimeter of the pusher.  While this would probably work well enough most of the time, even a small mis-alignment of the PU would result in the catastrophic destruction of the pusher.<br>
<br>
Also, I am generally less than impressed with the engine-out abort capability of Orion, especially within the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
Considering that GCNRs often exceed the ISP of Orion-type spacecraft, and can be done with even less new technology and engineering, I see no reason to push for the implementation of Orions.  If we really want large, heavy spacecraft with copious amount of disposable delta V, they could be done just as well with any number of propulsion schemes.<br>
<br>
Of course, they couldn't  be earth launched, but good luck getting Clarence for a ground-launched Orion anyway.<br>
<br>
Another advantage of most non-Orion propulsion mechanisms is they scale down nicely. <br>
<br>
An NTR or NEP drive could be used to launch a small, Mars-direct style manned craft within half a dozen years.<br>
<br>
For most near-term applications, an Orion sized craft would simply be overkill.  Despite higher unit costs, the total cost of an aggressive space program utilizing more modest craft powered by existing(I mean existing in the broad sense that operational prototypes have existed in the past, if not now) technologies could probably be done much cheaper. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orion@nuclearspace>Orion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/03 5:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=146>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Short term.</span><hr size=1> The way i see it nuclear pulse propulsion is decades away. There are other that should be developed first. Like something akin to the Liberty ship and alike. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/03 9:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=147>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Short term.</span><hr size=1> Theredcomin<br>
